Understanding interfaces in Java with example (checking what I learnt is correct)

Suppose we have an interface called `RemoteControl` that declares a method `turnOn()`:
```java
// Interface defining the RemoteControl contract
interface RemoteControl {
    void turnOn();
}
```
Now, we have two classes TV and AC, both of which implement the `RemoteControl` interface:
```java
// TV class implementing the RemoteControl interface
class TV implements RemoteControl {
    @Override
    public void turnOn() {
        System.out.println(&quot;TV is turned on&quot;);
    }
}

// AC class implementing the RemoteControl interface
class AC implements RemoteControl {
    @Override
    public void turnOn() {
        System.out.println(&quot;AC is turned on&quot;);
    }
}
```

Now, in the user code, we can interact with the TV and AC objects through the `RemoteControl` interface:
```java
public class UserCode {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        RemoteControl tvRemote = new TV(); // Create a TV object using the RemoteControl interface reference
        RemoteControl acRemote = new AC(); // Create an AC object using the RemoteControl interface reference

        tvRemote.turnOn(); // Calls the turnOn() method on the TV object
        acRemote.turnOn(); // Calls the turnOn() method on the AC object
    }
}
```
In this example, the `UserCode` class represents the user code that interacts with the TV and AC objects. And here user code creates objects of TV and AC classes using the `RemoteControl` interface reference.

By using the `RemoteControl` reference, is this where we say like --&gt; &quot; *User actually uses an interface (remote control) rather than interacting directly with classes (T.V class)*&quot;. 

So when we use this reference we are not actually instantiating T.V class but using and interface reference so that User can use it. And hence we achieve here total **Abstraction** ( if more functionalities were included ) by not interacting directly with T.V class but only interface. 

